            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>
                <date>May 31. 1854</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I am in Re-<lb/>-ceipt of your Letter by <persName>Mr.
                    Noah</persName>, &amp;<lb/> with regards to the Occident delivery,<lb/> I must
                say that it is not rightly ar-<lb/>-ranged yet. I assure you I do all<lb/> in my
                power for you, and ever more,<lb/> than my Business extends me time,<lb/> but the
                Post-office is so a mismanaged<lb/> concern, that if subscribers do not
                express-<lb/>-ly inquire for “Occident”, and merely<lb/> for Papers, they do not get
                them, and as<lb/> People in <placeName>California</placeName> care not a very<lb/>
                great deal of reading the same, with the<lb/> Exception of a fur, they neglect also
                of<lb/> trying to get and to call for them.</p>
            <p>I have a few names of subscribers to<lb/> the Oc to give you, <persName>Lewis
                    Bras</persName>, <persName>S. T.<lb/> Myer &amp; Co</persName>, <persName>A.
                    Hess &amp; Hamburger Bros.</persName>,<lb/> I believe however I have rendered
                long ago<lb/> already the names of the two first mentioned,<lb/>
                <persName>S. T. M &amp; Co</persName> and <persName>L Bros.</persName> I enclose
                you<lb/> a draft on <persName>C. R. &amp; Co</persName> for $50.00/100, I<lb/> meet
                with slow sale of Your Books,<lb/> and I would advise you, not to send</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>any more, even around the Hora<add>?</add>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The Emanu-El Congregation have<lb/> held a meeting on the
                        <date>18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of May</date><lb/> when the resignation of
                    <persName>Mr. M. Barnett</persName><lb/> was accepted from Vice Presidency,<lb/>
                and <persName>Mr. <hi rend="underline">A</hi>. <hi rend="underline">C</hi>.
                    Labatt</persName> (I believe <persName><hi rend="underline">A</hi>. <hi
                        rend="underline">C</hi>. L.</persName><lb/> in correct, it is at any Rate
                the old man)<lb/> was elected to fill the vacancy. Also<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Chas Emanuel</persName> has tendered his Re<lb/>-signation from the
                secretaryship, and ac-<lb/>-cepted, on account of his early intended<lb/> Departure
                for the states; his Loss, I<lb/> assure you will be severally felt in the<lb/>
                congregation, as he was the principal<lb/> in the whole congregation, who
                    promated<add>?</add> matters<lb/> and things with that zeal &amp; energy,
                which<lb/> are so promising for the Future Prosperity<lb/> of the Congregation; he
                has also labored<lb/> very diligently to work up the subscriptions<lb/> for building
                a synagogue, and in short<lb/> has done an inestimable amount of<lb/> good for the
                whole congregation; the con-<lb/>-gregation amounts to about 100 members,<lb/> and
                there is now more Interest exhibited by<lb/> them, than ever before; it has
                contracted for</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>the Building of a Synagogue at $19975,<lb/>
                <del>toward which</del> which amt. has nearly been subscribed<lb/> to amounts of
                averaging about $125—to $150—<lb/> at bearing an Interest of 6% pr. annum,<lb/>
                whilst money is worth here in <placeName>California</placeName><lb/> 3% pr. month.
                But the trouble the con-<lb/>-gregation has now, is to procure a<lb/> suitable
                Reader, such as they would<lb/> like to have, who would be able to de-<lb/>-liver an
                English as well as German<lb/> Discourse and in short a smart &amp;<lb/> learned man
                at a salary of $3500—<lb/> which I do think, as they seek a man,<lb/> entirely to
                little for <placeName>California</placeName>; however<lb/> I don't believe, there is
                any to be<lb/> found in <placeName>America</placeName> not at
                    <placeName>Europe</placeName>, who<lb/> could get off their situations &amp;
                come<lb/> hither. Married Jewish Families are<lb/> arriving with every steamer
                mostly, to settle<lb/> here, and we have quite a membership<add>?</add><lb/>
                already. I think I have never<lb/> furnished you since subjects to write<lb/> or say
                something about our <placeName>San Francisco</placeName><lb/> in your Occ. I
                remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Yours Truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">Cauffman &amp; Meyer</persName>
            </p>
